  "texts": [
    "Such as Transformer based methods (e.g., BERT, GPT) • Necessity for Abundant Annotated Data: Deep learning methods often require substantial volumes of data for effective training, which can be challenging and resource-intensive to obtain or create • High Computational Demands: Deep learning models are known for their computational hunger, often demanding significant processing power and resources, potentially limiting their practicality in resource-constrained environments • Black-box Nature and Lack of Transparency in Decision-Making: These methods often function as black-box models, lacking transparency in how they arrive at conclusions or make predictions, which can hinder interpretability and understanding of their inner workings • Difficulty in Handling Out-of-Domain Information: Deep learning models may struggle when confronted with data outside their trained domain, leading to potential inaccuracies or misinterpretations, especially when applied to unfamiliar or diverse datasets Hybrid approaches (Xu et al. 2019a; Yang et al.",
    "2020; Jia 2022a; Wu et al.",
    "2022, 2019b; Jiang et al.",
    "2013; Xianghua et al. 2013; Yan et al.",
    "2018; Wang et al."
